It’s estimated that at least 54 people die per day, due to air pollution caused by the mix of chemicals, dust, cars and hundreds of other pollutants. JOHANNESBURG - Fighting pollution doesn't take a break in winter. At least one expert says people need to be extra vigilant on colder days. READ: Environmental groups sue government over air pollution North West University's Geography and Environmental Studies' senior lecturer, Dr Roelof Burger said on cold days pollution increases. “Two things play into that: when it is so cold more people use solid fuels to heat up their homes. Also, on cold days, the atmosphere is so stable that we have no mixing...so today is particularly a bad day.”